{"key":"post-13121568","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13121568</id>\n<content>Fruits that are damaged may keep growing, but they don't repair the damage.&amp;nbsp; It didn't hurt the cake though and it will be fine.&amp;nbsp; There's growing evidence that roughing up a cake before first flush will produce more mushrooms.&amp;nbsp;  I like to see a few of you &lt;i&gt;P cubensis&lt;/i&gt; growers try this on half your cakes, while treating the other half gently as a control.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to keep the two groups separate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I know for a fact this is true with shiitake.&amp;nbsp; I 'spank' the substrate blocks after I strip the bags off.&amp;nbsp; I do this under rapidly running water.&amp;nbsp; I slap the hell out of all sides of the block, just to the point where if I hit any harder they'd break.&amp;nbsp; Doing this has upped my BE to 100% on the first flush.&amp;nbsp; I now do 1 flush and out, replacing the blocks with new ones, dramatically increasing yield per square foot per month, over traditional methods.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13122875</next>\n<prev>13120974</prev>\n<first>13120807</first>\n<last>13123729</last>\n<when>1283141046</when>\n<utime>08/30/10 07:04 AM</utime>\n</post>"}